</div>Good thinking <img src="images/smilies/thumbsup.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Thumbsup" class="inlineimg" />  Never can be too careful.<br />
<br />
<br />
I have a septic tank, and I don't want that dust in it. So i don't do anything in the house drains.  I use a 5 gal bucket with a bunch of holes in the bottom and just keep running the water hose through it. It is a pain in the <img src="images/smilies/pottytrain2.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Pottytrain2" class="inlineimg" /> <br />
<br />
I've done a few grows where I didn't adequately wash the dust, and it does make some nice perlite mud at the bottom. <img src="images/smilies/BangHead.gif" border="0" alt="" title="BangHead" class="inlineimg" />  <br />
<br />
I also haven't found an effective way of getting all the little capillary roots out of it so it can be reused. <img src="images/smilies/icon_scratch.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Icon Scratch" class="inlineimg" />
